lyzes Xenophon’s account of how Socrates’s life as a whole was just, in the sense of helping through his teaching a wide range of people. Socrates taught by never ceasing to raise, and to progress in answering, the fundamental and enduring civic questions: what is pious and impious, noble and ignoble, just and unjust, genuine statesmanship and genuine citizenship. Inspired by Hegel’s and Nietzsche’s assessments of Xenophon as the true voice of Socrates, The Socratic Way of Life establishes the Memorabilia as the groundwork of all subsequent political philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJustice. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aMemorabila.  aSocrates.  aXenophon.  acitizen-philosopher.  acourage.  ajustice.  amoderation.  apolitical philosophy.  astatesman.  avirtue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226516929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226516929/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles